You are working in /tmp/sv-eae311aa6b9e48a99d89f17e9d1be072/ShipmentTracker — a Blazor Web App scaffolded with `dotnet new blazor -int Auto -au Individual -f net10.0`. It has two projects:

- **ShipmentTracker** (server): ASP.NET Core host with Identity, EF Core (SQLite), Server+WASM render modes
- **ShipmentTracker.Client** (WASM): Client-side Blazor project

The app uses **InteractiveAuto** render mode (SSR on first load, then WebAssembly) with Individual accounts auth already configured. The server project references the client project.

## Task

Build a logistics shipment tracking application with these features:

### 1. Shared Models (in Client project so both sides can use them)

Create `ShipmentTracker.Client/Models/` with:

**ShipmentDto.cs**:
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Client.Models;

public class ShipmentDto
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public ShipmentStatus Status { get; set; }
    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public DateTime? ActualDelivery { get; set; }
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Description { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}

public enum ShipmentStatus
{
    Pending,
    PickedUp,
    InTransit,
    OutForDelivery,
    Delivered,
    Delayed
}

public class UpdateShipmentStatusDto
{
    public ShipmentStatus Status { get; set; }
}
```

### 2. Domain Entity & Database (Server project)

**Data/Shipment.cs** — EF entity:
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Data;

public class Shipment
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Status { get; set; } = "Pending";
    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public DateTime? ActualDelivery { get; set; }
    public string CustomerId { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Description { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public ApplicationUser? Customer { get; set; }
}
```

Update **ApplicationDbContext** to add `DbSet<Shipment> Shipments` and configure the entity in `OnModelCreating`.

### 3. API Endpoints (Server project)

Create **Endpoints/ShipmentEndpoints.cs** with a static extension method `MapShipmentApi(this WebApplication app)` that maps:

- `GET /api/shipments` — Dispatchers get all shipments; Customers get only their own (filter by authenticated user email). Requires auth.
- `GET /api/shipments/{trackingNumber}` — Public endpoint for tracking lookup by tracking number. No auth required.
- `PUT /api/shipments/{id}/status` — Dispatcher only. Updates shipment status. If status is "Delivered", set ActualDelivery to now.
- `POST /api/shipments` — Dispatcher only. Creates a new shipment with auto-generated tracking number (format: "SHP-" + 8 random uppercase alphanumeric chars).

All endpoints should map between the EF entity and ShipmentDto. Use `[Authorize]` and role checks via `RequireAuthorization()` as appropriate. Dispatchers have role "Dispatcher".

### 4. Seed Data & Roles (Server project)

Create **Data/SeedData.cs** with a static method `SeedAsync(IServiceProvider services)` that:
- Creates roles: "Dispatcher", "Customer"
